'''''Forbidden Forest''''' is a game designed by [[Paul Norman (game designer)|Paul Norman]], published by [[Cosmi Corporation]] in 1983 for the [[Commodore 64]] and [[Atari 8-bit computers]].

==Gameplay==
[[File:Forbidden_Forest_Atari_8-bit_PAL_screenshot.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot (Atari 8-bit)]]
In this game the player controls an archer, armed with a bow and a limit of four quivers of arrows per level. The aim is to move through a forest setting while eliminating various monsters, including giant spiders, bees, mutated frogs, dragons,<ref name="zzap64.co.uk">{{Cite web|url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/cgi-bin/displaypage.pl?issue=001&page=52&magazine=yr64|title=Redirecting}}</ref> wizards and snakes, with the [[Boss (video games)|final enemy]] being the [[Demogorgon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zzap64.co.uk/cgi-bin/displaypage.pl?issue=001&page=053&magazine=yr64|title = Redirecting}}</ref> The monsters were inspired by the films ''[[Night of the Demon]]'', ''[[Jason and the Argonauts (1963 film)|Jason and the Argonauts]]'', and ''[[Mysterious Island (1961 film)|Mysterious Island]]''.<ref name="Retro">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/RetroGamerIssue021-025/Retro_Gamer_Issue_025#page/n69/mode/2up|title=The Making Of... Forbidden Forest|author=Retro Gamer Team|magazine=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|date=January 2006|issue=25|pages=70â€“73}}</ref> The game has four levels of difficulty<ref name="zzap64.co.uk"/> (Innocent, Trooper, Daredevil and Crazy) which determine the number and speed of the monsters.

This is one of the earliest video games to use animated blood.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}  It also features parallax scrolling and a day/night cycle.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQ3VAAAAQBAJ&q=Day+night+cycle+forbidden+forest&pg=PA10|title = Virtual Landscapes: The Embryonic Era|isbn = 9780957408630|last1 = Ali|first1 = Umran|date = 19 September 2013| publisher=Umran Ali }}</ref>

==Development==
Paul Norman began working for a small company named Synchro. It was a small software store creating Apple II, VIC-20 and Commodore 64 software. Paul rented a vehicle and drove the 30 miles to apply for an advertised position with a game he had created for the VIC-20. Paul landed the position and began working on ''Forbidden Forest'' as a way of learning 6502 programming. The company that he was working for was going out of business and representatives from the software company Cosmi arrived to purchase office furniture. They saw Paul working on ''Forbidden Forest'' and hired him on the spot.<ref>{{cite web
  | publisher = C64.com
  | title = Interview with Paul Norman
  | url = http://www.c64.com/interviews/norman.html
  | accessdate = 2012-10-27}}</ref>

